      <title>Cancoillotte’s comeback is no surprise | Letters</title>
      <link>https://www.theguardian.com/food/2026/may/22/cancoillottes-comeback-is-no-surprise</link>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Readers respond to an article about France’s ‘viral’ liquid cheese&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Yes, we French people do value taste in cheeses (&lt;a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2026/may/18/france-fitness-craze-cancoillotte-cheese"&gt;The French are hitting their protein goals – thanks to a cheese that looks like ectoplasm, 18 May&lt;/a&gt;). There is a myriad of flavours in our dairy industry, from extreme farmhouse dungy-funk to sterilised stinky plastic. But most of our industrial cheeses sit firmly in the vicinity of savoury hardened fat.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;So it’s no surprise that cancoillotte is making a comeback! In Paris in my late 20s, every single night out (or in) started with an &lt;em&gt;apéro dînatoire&lt;/em&gt; (drinks and snacks). And cancoillotte was a staple. Why? Because if you &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4KrUxLBHVu8"&gt;&lt;em&gt;microwavay&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; it for 30 seconds, you get a great cheese dip for chips, bread, veggies, spoons. Cheap, tasty enough and quick. And now it’s deemed healthy? I rest my case.&lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mel Garcon&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;Sazeray, France&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;a href="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2026/may/22/cancoillottes-comeback-is-no-surprise"&gt;Continue reading...&lt;/a&gt;</description>
