      <title>Trash hits! Why a wave of hedonistic, feral female pop stars are rejecting respectability</title>
      <link>https://www.theguardian.com/music/2026/may/22/trash-hits-hedonistic-feral-female-pop-stars-rejecting-respectability-slayyyter-cobrah</link>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;In a collapsing world, artists like Slayyyter and Cobrah are chasing extreme highs with hyperactive music and debauched lyrics. Is their trashy vibe emancipating – or a bit contrived?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;If any year demanded a soundtrack of self-aggrandising female mayhem, it’s 2026. Amid the terrors of war, AI and the climate crisis, women are expected to be symbolic vessels of order and stability: thin, beautiful and perpetually 25 – a state of perfection newly available for purchase thanks to weight-loss drugs and the &lt;a href="https://www.theguardian.com/wellness/2025/jun/27/what-is-a-deep-plane-facelift"&gt;deep plane facelift&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Covered unironically in leopard print and rhinestones, a cohort of young female pop stars are defying this familiar con with brash electronic pop, shamelessly hedonistic lyrics, anarchic sexuality and an obsession with what was once dismissed as “white trash”. It’s an aesthetic embraced by performers &lt;a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2026/mar/27/slayyyter-worst-girl-in-america-interview"&gt;such as Slayyyter&lt;/a&gt;, Kim Petras, Cobrah, Demi Lovato, Snow Strippers’ Tatiana Schwaninger, Tove Lo and returning scene godmother Kesha.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2026/may/22/trash-hits-hedonistic-feral-female-pop-stars-rejecting-respectability-slayyyter-cobrah"&gt;Continue reading...&lt;/a&gt;</description>
